Every concept from the series, in one coherent flow — from button click to database and back.

We’ve covered a lot of ground across this series.
Ubiquitous Language gave ShopFlow a shared vocabulary enforced everywhere in code. Bounded Contexts drew clean lines between the six business areas. Value Objects eliminated primitive obsession. Entities gave domain objects stable identity. Aggregates enforced business rules in one place. The Repository and Anti-Corruption Layer protected the domain from the API. Domain Events decoupled post-checkout side effects. Module Architecture made the boundaries stick with ESLint and barrel files.
Now let’s see all of it at once.
We’ll trace one user action — “Add to Cart” — through every layer of ShopFlow from the button click to the re-rendered item count badge.

The Full Flow
User clicks "Add to Cart"
│
▼
ProductCardComponent.addToCart()
│ dispatches
▼
CartActions.itemAdded({ productId, variantId, quantity })
│
▼
CartEffects.addItem$
├── CartRepository.findByCustomer() ← abstract class
│ └── CartApiRepository → GET /api/v1/customers/{id}/cart
│ └── CartMapper.toDomain(dto) ← ACL: DTO → Aggregate
│
├── cart.addItem(...) ← domain command
│ └── enforces MAX_QUANTITY_PER_ITEM
│ └── returns Result<void, DomainError>
│
├── CartRepository.save(cart)
│ └── CartMapper.toSaveDTO(cart) ← ACL: Aggregate → DTO
│ └── CartApiRepository → PUT /api/v1/carts/{id}
│
└── cart.pullDomainEvents()
└── eventBus.publish(CartItemAdded)
└── AnalyticsListener → tracks 'add_to_cart'
│
▼
CartActions.itemAddSucceeded({ cart: cartDTO })
│
▼
CartReducer updates store state
│
▼
selectCartItemCount recomputes
│
▼
CartBadgeComponent re-renders with new countNine layers. Each with a single, well-defined responsibility.

Layer 1: The Component
The component captures intent and delegates. Nothing else.
// catalog/presentation/product-card/product-card.component.ts
@Component({
selector: 'shopflow-product-card',
standalone: true,
imports: [MoneyFormatPipe],
template: `
<div class="product-card">
<img [src]="product.primaryImageUrl" [alt]="product.name" />
<h3>{{ product.name }}</h3>
<p>{{ product.price | moneyFormat }}</p>
@if (!product.isAvailable) {
<p class="out-of-stock">Out of stock</p>
}
<button
(click)="addToCart()"
[disabled]="!product.isAvailable || adding()"
>
{{ adding() ? 'Adding…' : 'Add to Cart' }}
</button>
@if (error()) {
<p class="error">{{ error() }}</p>
}
</div>
`
})
export class ProductCardComponent {
@Input() product!: CatalogProduct;
readonly adding = signal(false);
readonly error = signal<string | null>(null);
private cartFacade = inject(CartFacade);
addToCart(): void {
if (!this.product.isAvailable) return;
this.adding.set(true);
this.error.set(null);
this.cartFacade.addItem(
this.product.id,
this.product.variants[0].variantId,
this.product.variants[0].price,
1,
);
}
}Notice what the component does not do. It doesn’t call HttpClient. It doesn't know what MAX_QUANTITY_PER_ITEM is. It doesn't construct domain objects. It asks product.isAvailable — the domain model answers.
Signals handle local UI state. The NgRx store handles domain state.

Layer 2: The Facade
// cart/application/cart.facade.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartFacade {
readonly itemCount$ = this.store.select(selectCartItemCount);
readonly total$ = this.store.select(selectCartTotal);
readonly isEmpty$ = this.store.select(selectCartIsEmpty); constructor(private store: Store) {}
addItem(productId: ProductId, variantId: string, unitPrice: Money, quantity: number): void {
this.store.dispatch(CartActions.itemAdded({
productId: productId.value,
variantId,
unitPriceMinor: unitPrice.amountInMinorUnits,
currency: unitPrice.currency,
quantity,
}));
}
removeItem(cartItemId: CartItemId): void {
this.store.dispatch(CartActions.itemRemoved({ cartItemId: cartItemId.value }));
}
checkout(): void {
this.store.dispatch(CartActions.checkoutInitiated());
}
}
Components import CartFacade from cart/index.ts. Nothing else from the cart context is accessible to them.

Layer 3: The Effect
The effect coordinates. It hydrates the aggregate, executes the command, checks the result, persists, and publishes events. It has no business logic of its own.
addItem$ = createEffect(() =>
this.actions$.pipe(
ofType(CartActions.itemAdded),
withLatestFrom(this.store.select(selectCurrentCustomerId)),
switchMap(([action, customerId]) =>
this.cartRepository.findByCustomer(customerId).pipe(
switchMap(existingCart => {
const cart = existingCart ?? Cart.createEmpty(customerId, action.currency);
const result = cart.addItem(
CartItemId.generate(),
new ProductId(action.productId),
action.productName,
action.variantId,
Money.ofMinorUnits(action.unitPriceMinor, action.currency),
new Quantity(action.quantity),
);
if (!result.success) {
return of(CartActions.itemAddFailed({
error: { code: result.error.code, message: result.error.message, type: 'domain' }
}));
}
return this.cartRepository.save(cart).pipe(
tap(() => cart.pullDomainEvents().forEach(e => this.eventBus.publish(e))),
map(saved => CartActions.itemAddSucceeded({ cart: toCartDTO(saved) })),
catchError(err =>
of(CartActions.itemAddFailed({
error: { code: err.code ?? 'UNEXPECTED_ERROR', message: err.message, type: 'application' }
}))
)
);
})
)
)
)
);The effect knows when to call the aggregate. It doesn’t know how the aggregate makes decisions. Business logic stays in the aggregate. Coordination stays in the effect.

Layer 4: The Aggregate
cart.addItem() enforces the rules — max quantity, cart status, distinct item limit — and returns a Result. The effect checks it and routes accordingly. We built the full Cart aggregate in the Aggregates article.

Layer 5: The Repository and Mapper

• CartRepository.findByCustomer() → CartApiRepository → GET /api/v1/customers/{id}/cart → CartMapper.toDomain(dto) → Cart

• CartRepository.save(cart) → CartMapper.toSaveDTO(cart) → CartApiRepository → PUT /api/v1/carts/{id}
The mapper translates unit_price_minor to Money. It translates OPEN to 'open'. The aggregate never sees a DTO. The component never sees an HTTP response.

Layer 6: The Reducer and Selectors
export const cartReducer = createReducer(
initialCartState,
on(CartActions.itemAdded, state => ({ ...state, loading: true, error: null })),
on(CartActions.itemAddSucceeded, (state, { cart }) => ({ ...state, cart, loading: false })),
on(CartActions.itemAddFailed, (state, { error }) => ({ ...state, loading: false, error }))
);
// Selectors reconstruct Value Objects on the way out
export const selectCartItemCount = createSelector(
selectCartState,
state => state.cart?.items.reduce((n, i) => n + i.quantity, 0) ?? 0
);
export const selectCartTotal = createSelector(
selectCartState,
state => state.cart ? Money.fromJSON(state.cart.total) : Money.zero('EUR')
);
Domain Events: The Side Effects
After the save, CartItemAdded is published. The Analytics listener picks it up independently — no changes to the Cart module needed:
this.eventBus.on<CartItemAdded>('CartItemAdded').subscribe(event => {
this.analyticsProvider.track('add_to_cart', {
productId: event.productId,
quantity: event.quantity,
});
});
The Decision Guide
When a new feature arrives, use this to decide what to apply:
SituationApply ThisSimple read-only feature, no business rulesService + component. Skip the DDD overhead.A primitive represents a domain concept with constraintsValue ObjectA concept has stable identity over timeEntityMultiple related objects share invariantsAggregate RootBusiness logic appearing in componentsMove it to the domain modelAPI shape differs from domain modelMapper (Anti-Corruption Layer)Multiple contexts react to one eventDomain EventsWrong imports crossing context linesESLint boundary rulesSame word means different things in different areasSeparate Bounded ContextsThree or more contexts share the exact same typeConsider the Shared Kernel

What the Architecture Actually Gives You
Testability. Every layer is independently testable. Unit test the aggregate with zero mocks. Test the mapper with raw DTOs. Test effects with a mock repository. Test components with a mock facade.
Changeability. The backend renames unit_price_minor to price_cents. You change one line in CartMapper. The aggregate, the components, the selectors — untouched.
Navigability. A new developer joins. They read cart/index.ts and understand the public API. They read cart/domain/cart.aggregate.ts and understand the business rules. No need to grep the entire codebase.
Confidence. ESLint boundary rules mean a wrong import fails the build. The architecture enforces itself.

Where to Start
Don’t apply all of this at once. The highest leverage moves, in order:
Ubiquitous Language — agree on names and enforce them everywhere. Zero setup cost. Immediate payoff.
Bounded Contexts + barrel files — draw the lines and back them with ESLint. Prevents the slow coupling death.
Value Objects — start with Money and your typed IDs. Eliminates a whole bug category immediately.
Add Entities, Aggregates, Repositories, and Domain Events when the complexity justifies them. The goal is code that scales with the business and makes sense to the people who build it.
ShopFlow did exactly that. So can your application.

